HLC Homework 2: Plotting

For the second homework, your goal will to replicate the below plot to the best of your ability using the gapminder data frame and ggplot2.

This plot is more complicated than any of the examples we have shown during class, so we will provide hints and walk through how to replicate it in steps.

In addition to the hints that will be given, make use of your resources from the HLC markdown documents we have gone over in class, R for data science, and Google. Remember that you can access the R documentation for any function by typing ? before the name of the function in the R console, or by searching for the function in the search box of the Help tab of the bottom right corner of R Studio.

Steps for creating the plot

Step 1

Create your own new R markdown document (.Rmd file) or R script (.R file) to run the code for this homework response. If you are using a .Rmd file, remember that you must run R code in the gray code blocks. We went over how to create these during class.

Step 2

Load the gapminder and ggplot2 package contents into R. Remember that to load package contents into R, we use the library function.

Step 3

Run the below code to subset of the Gapminder data for the years 1952 and 2007. This will be the data frame that you supply to ggplot() in later steps. We will cover subsetting data frames in more detail next week.

homeworkData <- dplyr::filter(gapminder, year %in% c(1952, 2007))

Step 4

We will be plotting life expectancy (lifeExp) vs GDP per capita (gdpPercap) for this data. Start by replicating the below plot, referencing the examples we covered during class as needed.

Step 5

Now, lets color the points by continent and scale the size of the points by population. Again, reference the examples where we did this in class as needed.

Step 6

Notice that many of the points are overlapping each other. If we would like to see where points overlap, we can alter the transparency with the alpha parameter. alpha is a value that ranges from 0 (fully transparent) to 1 (fully opaque). In the geom_point() part of your code, supply alpha = 0.5 outside of the mapping aes() specification. Your plot should now look like the one below.

Step 7

In the above plot, you may have noticed that the GDP per capita data on the x-axis is mostly concentrated towards 0, with some large data outliers. It might be better to transform the y-axis into a log scale. Lets set a log10 scale x-axis for our plot. Hint: the function scale_x_log10() may be useful here.

Your plot should now look like this:

Step 8

It looks like there is a linear trend between life expectancy and GDP per capita. We can add a linear trendline to our plot to show this relationship. To do this, we will want to make use of the geom_smooth function. You can read more about how to use geom_smooth to plot a linear trendline here and by looking at the R documentation for this function. Bonus: hide the shaded confidence region with the se parameter, change the line color to black, and set the line type to be dashed.

Your plot will now look like this:

You may get a message in R that says: geom_smooth() using formula 'y ~ x'. You can ignore this.

Step 9

Notice that all of our labels by default are using the column name. We want to make these more descriptive. Lets change the x-axis label to GDP per capita and the y-axis label to Life expectancy. Lets also add a title that says Life expectancy increases independently of GDP per cap. We discussed how to do this in class.

We also would like to change the legend labels to Continent and Population. Hint: there are three different ways to do this described here.

Your plot should now look like this:

Step 10

If you remember from the beginning, we filtered the gapminder data set to only contain data from the years 1952 and 2007. We want to see if the trend of life expectancy by GDP per capita is different between these two years by plotting the data for each year side-by-side. We can do this by using facets to show the different years. We havent covered this in class, but try looking at the R help page for the facet_wrap function to make your plot look like the one below:

Step 11

ggplot2 has a theme system which allows you to have control over the non-data elements of your plot such as ticks, panel strips, and backgrounds. Themes can help you make the plot aesthetically pleasing or match an existing style guide. By default, ggplot2 uses a theme called theme_grey(). This theme gives us the gray background weve been seeing in our plot. We can change this theme to any one of the ggplot2 inbuilt complete themes which controll all non-data display.

Try experimenting with the theme. Run ?theme_grey in the R console to see a help page with the complete list of theme options.

To match the plot below, change the theme to theme_bw().

Step 12

Finally, we can use the theme() function if we want to tweak components of our existing theme. One common component that you may want to change is the text size. Add the below code to your ggplot to resize the axis text to 12, the axis title text to 14, and the facet title text to 14.

theme(strip.text.x = element_text(size = 14),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 14))
